## ASP.NET Core (.NET 8) Migration

### Key Breaking Changes

| .NET Framework | ASP.NET Core | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `Response.End()` | Return `IActionResult` | `Thread.Abort()` removed entirely from .NET Core |
| `Response.Redirect(url, true)` | Return `RedirectResult` | No `endResponse` parameter; no thread abort |
| `Response.Write(data)` | Return `FileContentResult` | Pipeline is result-based, not imperative |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | **Delete it** | Can never be thrown — dead code that hides bugs |
| `Response.AddHeader(...)` | `Response.Headers.Append(...)` | API rename |
| Web Forms event handlers | Controller actions + routes | Web Forms doesn't exist in Core |

### Migrated Code

```csharp
using Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc;
using System.Text;

public class ReportController : Controller
{
    // POST /report/export
    [HttpPost]
    public IActionResult Export()
    {
        var data = GenerateReport();
        var bytes = Encoding.UTF8.GetBytes(data);

        // File() handles Content-Disposition, Content-Type, and
        // terminates the response — no Response.End() needed.
        return File(bytes, "text/csv", "report.csv");
    }

    // POST /report/redirect
    [HttpPost]
    public IActionResult RedirectAction()
    {
        if (!User.Identity?.IsAuthenticated ?? true)
        {
            // Returns 302 — no thread abort, no exception.
            return Redirect("/login");
        }

        try
        {
            ProcessRequest();
            return Redirect("/success");
        }
        // No ThreadAbortException catch — it cannot exist in .NET 8.
        catch (Exception ex)
        {
            LogError(ex);
            return Redirect("/error");
        }
    }
}
```

### Critical Pitfalls

**1. Code after `Redirect()` now executes**
```csharp
// .NET Framework — code after this NEVER runs (thread aborted)
Response.Redirect("/login", true);
SensitiveOperation(); // unreachable

// .NET 8 — code after this DOES run (it just sets a header)
Response.Redirect("/login"); // ⚠️ SensitiveOperation() WILL execute
SensitiveOperation();

// Fix: always return the result immediately
return Redirect("/login");
```

**2. `Response.End()` has no equivalent — and you don't need one**
```csharp
// Old pattern — imperative, exception-driven flow
Response.Write(data);
Response.End(); // throws ThreadAbortException to halt pipeline

// New pattern — return a result; the framework handles the rest
return Content(data, "text/csv");
```

**3. Swallowed `ThreadAbortException` blocks masked real bugs**
```csharp
// This old pattern silently ate errors if ProcessRequest() threw
// an exception whose type name contained "Thread":
catch (ThreadAbortException) { /* swallow */ }

// In .NET 8, remove it entirely. If you had logic depending on
// this, it was already broken — audit your ProcessRequest() code.
```

**4. `User.Identity` can be `null` in .NET 8**
```csharp
// Old: User.Identity.IsAuthenticated — safe because Identity was
//      always non-null in System.Web
// New: Identity CAN be null if no auth middleware is configured
if (!User.Identity?.IsAuthenticated ?? true)
```

**5. Prefer `[Authorize]` over manual auth checks**
```csharp
[Authorize]
[HttpPost]
public IActionResult RedirectAction()
{
    // Framework returns 401/redirect before your code runs.
    // No manual IsAuthenticated check needed.
    ProcessRequest();
    return Redirect("/success");
}
```

The core mental model shift: .NET Framework used **imperative response writing** with thread aborts for flow control. ASP.NET Core uses **return values** (`IActionResult`) — the method returns a result object, and the framework writes the response after your code completes cleanly.
